1
00:00:05,520 --> 00:00:32,380
Hello, SF Tech Week people. We're going to talk about founder sales in the AI era today, and we're kind of going to take an approach of talking about how these companies are built with the founder-led sales motion. Joined here today by my co-founder, Keith, who, if you don't know, previously worked on Instagram and Facebook and built the camera and a lot of things you might use every day. Kayvon, who previously founder of Periscope.

2
00:00:32,380 --> 00:00:54,910
And also grew Twitter to many more users than when he joined. And then Will, who famously fought money laundering at Facebook, and also led payments teams on WhatsApp, and now founder of Greenlight. So excited to hear a little bit about each one of these founders' stories here.

3
00:00:54,910 --> 00:01:19,300
And maybe shed some light on the journey from having an idea, wanting to start a company, figuring out who you're going to serve with that company, like the right people, and then what the company needs to become in order to actually serve them. So excited to get into that with you guys. Before we do, maybe just to give everyone some color, we'd love to maybe hear a little bit about the things that people are building. Cool, let's get into it.

4
00:01:19,300 --> 00:01:46,960
Thanks everyone for coming. My name is Kayvon, and I was previously the founder of Periscope, led product and engineering at Twitter for many years, and now we're building a product called Macroscope. So at a high level, Macroscope is what we like to say, it's an understanding engine for your company. So if you are a company that builds software, as I'm sure many people in this room are, you probably have lots of questions that you ask on a daily or weekly basis like,

5
00:01:46,960 --> 00:02:09,889
What progress did we make on our priorities? And how did the code base change? And what is everyone on the team working on? Now, most companies, whether you're an enormously large company like Twitter or you're a small startup like us, the state-of-the-art way that you solve this problem is meetings and tickets in Jira and Linear and status updates over Slack.

6
00:02:09,889 --> 00:02:38,220
And what we do with Macroscope is we answer these questions for you automatically using the actual code base as the source of truth. So when you install Macroscope, you link your GitHub, you link your Slack, you link your Linear or Jira if you have it, and we build you a story automatically of what is happening at your company. So would love for anyone here to give it a whirl. You can install Macroscope on our website. We have a two-week free trial, and let me know what you think. Send me a DM on Twitter.

7
00:02:39,980 --> 00:03:08,020
Insights on product analytics are really useful. We use them to help write a lot of our customer feedback, just looking at what our engineering team is shipping every week. So it's actually a really useful tool. Thanks, Kayvon. And Will, would you mind taking a couple of minutes to just share what you guys do? Can I stand for a moment? I don't know, just got to see everyone. We sell to banks. So at Greenlight, we sell enterprise contracts to bank compliance and risk teams. Meaning our product does not look nearly, nearly as nice as that.

8
00:03:08,020 --> 00:03:37,760
In fact, the GreenLine product doesn't look like very much at all. And we build AI agents. Agents live inside of your existing tools at a bank or a fintech platform. So quick question for the audience as we're going to go into founder sales here. How many people are doing enterprise contracts? I might categorize that as like $250,000 plus contracts. Okay. That's the world that we occupy. We have dozens of customers, not hundreds or thousands. Companies like Coinbase, Ramp, Mercury use us every day in production. Happy to talk about those user paradigms that we're really excited about.

9
00:03:37,760 --> 00:04:05,380
But I think there's a ton of opportunity building AI agents for the enterprise space. Even though it's less visible from the outside, there are really exciting things taking place in that world. So that's all I'll say. I'll save it for the panel. Thanks. And Keith? Great. I guess I'll tell you all a little bit about Lightfield. You know, Henry and I have been working on it for a while. I'd say that maybe the origin story, before we say exactly what we do, is that our first product was an AI presentations product, Tome.

10
00:04:05,380 --> 00:04:32,190
You know, we scaled it very quickly. And I think we had two really interesting learnings from it that really led us to wanting to build Lightfield. I'm getting some signal to stand up. The first one was obviously that we, sort of this technical insight of, you know, context construction is really, really important to be able to do great knowledge work. So we're like, we want to build a great context engine so that we can do real, high-quality, generative AI for people.

11
00:04:32,190 --> 00:04:57,860
And then the other one was more company building insight of, you know, we had sort of gone through a pretty massive pivot in the past two years. And one of the hardest things about pivoting your company is honestly navigating the fog of war. And like, what does that mean? You know, when you're trying to figure out what to build, who to serve, how to sell it, there's so much data and noise in the world that you don't have to make sense of.

12
00:04:57,860 --> 00:05:27,150
You know, for us, you know, we were a big team. We had like 70 people. And, you know, when you have a lot of people at your company, it's hard to get to ground truth, right? You have some people that speak to customers, some people that speak to prospects, you know, we have some people that like speak on social, and then all of those people make a deck for you like once a month and give you insights that are supposed to teach you what to build. And of course, none of those people are engineers. And, you know, none of those people are

13
00:05:27,150 --> 00:05:47,020
People are people that can actually construct the product. And we're like, oh, this actually seems like a broken part of company building right now. But the people who build the software are out of touch with the customers they serve and the prospects that they want to serve. So we started to reimagine, you know, could we reinvent?

14
00:05:47,020 --> 00:06:06,480
The idea of like a boring old CRM to become the source of ground truth and customer memory that you could run your whole company on so that you would be able to keep honing like who do I serve, how do I speak to them, like what should we build next, and how do we know that it's working?

15
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:35,390
So that's what we've been building for the past, I would say, 18 months. And it's been going really well. We'd say we have hundreds of customers so far. It's free for four more weeks. So if you're interested in trying it, reach out to one of the people with the Lightfield jacket. So that's why we're excited to chat with all of you today. Let's get into the discussion. So I mean, I think maybe some good background color to get everyone...

16
00:06:35,390 --> 00:07:03,980
Will, I don't know if you want to kick us off here. Why compliance? Why Greenline? Yeah, happy to. I wanted to start a company for a long time. I've always enjoyed building, and when I knew I wanted to do that, I looked at the area where I had some expertise. I used to be on the product team for anti-money laundering over at Facebook Payments, and so you build a lot of unique domain knowledge working.

17
00:07:03,980 --> 00:07:30,740
Fighting terrorists and catching money laundering. And so the journey to understand what we build with Greenlight and the sales journey was actually the same journey. I spent the first like three to four months while I was still in my last job just interviewing anyone who would talk to me who worked in compliance, risk, or some form of anti-money laundering profession. I would kind of do the mom test. So for anyone, I highly recommend the mom test if anyone hasn't read it. It's a great book on customer discovery. It's effectively talking to people and saying like, where do you spend your time doing?

18
00:07:30,740 --> 00:07:54,400
What are the things keeping you up at night today? Open-ended questions to understand pain points. After about 30 or 40 of those, I think I had a pretty good understanding of what some of those pain points were. And we ended up building several different prototypes. The first version we built of Greenlight was a completely different idea. Put it in front of those people. They're like, yeah, this is cool. This is like priority number 20 for me. Okay, great. Let's try the next one. Next one, we want to go out and try to prototype as priority number nine.

19
00:07:54,400 --> 00:08:23,730
And I was like, okay, we're going in the right direction, but still not important enough. And then we got to something that was like, oh, this solves my immediate pain point, which that person who said that thing became our first customer. So I think maybe, especially if it has a B2B company, early sales and early discovery are actually the same thing. I'm a product person. Early product discovery is the same as early sales. So that's how we got to the idea for Greenlight back in summer of 2023. Awesome. Kayvon, what about you?

20
00:08:24,050 --> 00:08:47,600
A lot of the same. The only thing I would add, given the product that we build, we have the luxury of being customers of our own product. And frankly, everything I've ever built in my life, that property has been true for. I've built consumer apps before, even my first B2B company. It was a very selfish process. We just wanted to be users of a product that didn't exist, and so we went out and built it.

21
00:08:47,600 --> 00:09:16,690
And I think that philosophy actually works for a surprisingly long time. Even at Twitter, there was truth to prioritizing our most ambitious ideas that way. I think it can fall apart also when you have an app that hundreds of millions of people are using. But I think in the case of Macroscope, we just live this problem viscerally. I was the head of product at Twitter, and I spent most of my time just understanding what the fuck people were working on. It's actually a really hard problem.

22
00:09:16,690 --> 00:09:43,940
When you have thousands of engineers at a company, even my engineering partners would have no idea. I could tell you on any given day what the top five most important priorities were, but I would have no idea whether our engineering allocation was actually aligned to those priorities. The head of engineering, the process of getting to that ground truth is basically a game of telephone. It's like you ask your senior managers who ask their tech leads who go distract a bunch of engineers from building stuff to go,

23
00:09:43,940 --> 00:10:11,740
Answer questions to fill out a report that's old by the time, it's stale by the time it's put together. And so having lived this pain, we, you know, our team, when we started building the product, really just wanted to kind of decompose those problems into the most granular parts that would be useful to us as a small team, because obviously a five-person engineering team has very different problems than a multi-thousand-person engineering team. But we set out to build like a skateboard or a tricycle, like it's, you know.

24
00:10:11,740 --> 00:10:39,420
More nascent incarnations of what the product has now turned into. The first barometer was, is this useful for us as a five-person team? Then as soon as we could say yes to that question, we would go out and reach out to all the customers we talked to in our process of doing research. We talked to public company engineering team leads, to all of our startup friends that were building companies, and asking them similar sorts of things like, what problems do you face in this area?

25
00:10:39,420 --> 00:11:07,580
And we would just sort of like slowly increase the size of customer that we would reach out to and say like, does this solve the problem for you? And that was surprisingly useful. Like we started with companies that were five-person engineering teams and eventually were able to build features that were useful to 15-person engineering teams. And now we have multi-hundred-person engineering teams using the product and we kind of had to just gradually go chip away at the problems until we could, you know, they could say yes to that.

26
00:11:07,580 --> 00:11:36,380
I mean, that really resonates. I think we're going to talk about ground truth a lot in this discussion. But I think sort of on a meta level, like I feel like that's very much like what inspired us to do this too. And that like, it feels like once your company gets to a certain level of maturity like that head of product scenario you were describing, it's so hard to get the ground truth of what customers want or what users want, right? And so I think just like it was hard for you to get the ground truth of what people were building. So I think that kind of motivated us.

27
00:11:36,380 --> 00:12:05,470
I don't know, Keith, if you want to share how we got to our first few customers with Lightfield. Yeah. I mean, I think one of the biggest challenges of building something as broad as an AI CRM is that you're just never done from a feature perspective, right? And, you know, right now, I would say that we've got a product that a lot of people use every day and they like, but that wasn't the case a year ago. So we sort of needed to cheat a little, right? And I think one piece of it was identifying folks that were really underserved.

28
00:12:05,470 --> 00:12:33,260
Because, you know, I think we started a little upmarket. You know, we started with these, like, larger companies, and we found that larger companies go-to-market are incredibly over-served, right? Like, every go-to-market department in a tech company has, like, 50 tools, and there's, like, another 500 that want to get in. So they're actually incredibly over-served, so it's very easy to get a pilot, and it's very hard to go from pilot to them paying for something.

29
00:12:33,260 --> 00:12:57,250
So we're like, let's find a group of people that actually all of this stuff doesn't work for. And it just so happens that that was us. We had to cobble together some go-to-market tooling to understand our customers, and it was brutal. So we wanted to build something for ourselves. And then the other part was, honestly, the product was so early.

30
00:12:57,250 --> 00:13:25,280
At the start of the year that we had to do some things that didn't scale. One of the things that I'm more proud of in our journey was that we inherited this big office from our last company. And at first there was kind of this stench. I remember we had this salesperson who worked here. He was like, wow, it smells like dead unicorn in here. And then when we were pivoting, a lot of the team was complaining about how this reminded them of good times. We decided to like...

31
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:46,460
We weaponized that, so we decided to give the office space away for free to anyone that would use our product. And we had some strange people show up, and then we also had some great people show up, you know, who sort of had a moral obligation to at least try our CRM for like a month.

32
00:13:46,460 --> 00:14:13,490
Through that, we got a lot of feedback, and then we eventually got to a state where they liked it, and then we asked them for referrals, and I think that's when we started to host again and start to get people to care. Yeah, I think competitive space is actually a really interesting question in the context of getting your first customers. Will, I'm super curious. There's a handful of compliance companies out there that make that easier. How did you convince your first few to go with you specifically?

33
00:14:13,490 --> 00:14:38,290
I'll say there's less than there are go-to-market companies. So I'm a huge fan of solving super boring problems. Sometimes we'll describe greenlight. We do AI for compliance teams at banks, and I can see the eyes of the person I'm speaking to glaze over in real time. And I love that because ultimately the competition we face is not as meaningful or good, frankly, as some of the competition that I think you face in sexier things. Sometimes I think like we did YC.

34
00:14:38,290 --> 00:15:06,990
Had a lot of 21-year-old founders. Awesome. That's great. None of them were building compliance software for banks. And so in that way allowed us to really focus on what is the pain that we're trying to solve. In many ways, you don't really differentiate on how advanced frontier AI you're bringing to this use case. How well can you solve this problem repeatedly many times before? And as soon as we were able to solve that problem, it became pretty clear. Maybe I'll make a general comment as we're talking about AI and the positioning of these types of companies.

35
00:15:06,990 --> 00:15:32,880
Generally speaking, I think agents are going to be most useful when they do the same work as a human counterpart. For us, we do AI compliance analysts or AI risk analysts. Those workflows as they exist today exist outside of current tooling. So my team at Facebook, we had all this great technology we built, but then we also had thousands of people doing risk and compliance operations. So the question is like, what are those people doing all day long? And it's starting to codify in those workflows.

36
00:15:32,880 --> 00:15:54,260
And so while there was competition in like the areas that have already been brought into software world, there's a lot of problems that have not yet been to software world. Our belief here is that, I think I've heard this before, but it's worth repeating, the exciting thing about AI is it's going to essentially bring out data that hasn't been possible to use before. Specifically for us, that's knowledge inside the head of white collar workers.

37
00:15:54,260 --> 00:16:19,790
There's a lot of knowledge tapped there that has not been used for training or for scaled software. And so we're really excited about that. And by doing that, we don't end up competing with existing software. We tend to compete with things like outsourced BPOs and managed services, which we just have a huge edge on in terms of speed and scale that we can support. Yeah, so it sounds like it's a completely like orthogonal framing to like, you know, I'm just going to buy a compliance thing or I'm going to hire an agency to help us do this.

38
00:16:19,790 --> 00:16:46,690
But I will say, especially to founders in the room, like, nailing that positioning is absolutely critical. Because when we jump on a call, within the first five minutes, I want to convince them that we are completely different than all the software they already own. And if you fail to do that, you don't escape that world. So, like, we have, like, a specific slide I have where I'm like, this is what you have today, this is why we're different, and we layer on top, or we do this. That was a huge unlock for us. As soon as we got our positioning right, the conversation just became a lot easier. Makes sense.

39
00:16:46,690 --> 00:17:12,099
And how many revs did it take you to get the positioning right? Probably 80 to 100 sales calls. I closed our first two and a half million of revenue myself, and that was really fun. Again, as product discovery in addition to sales. But every time I got one or 2% better, and now it became easier such that when we ramped up our first, we have seven AEs today. Our first two AEs, they could just take my playbook and run with it. It's not lost.

40
00:17:12,099 --> 00:17:35,810
It's not lost doing those reps. So we were able to turn that into something quite useful. That's awesome. I mean, it feels like macroscope is kind of similar in that. I don't think it's like going up head-to-head against anything I've heard about before, like as like a way to understand what the product team is building. Curious how you sort of position it to your first customers. Yeah, I mean, we really have two, if you were to really simplify our product down, there's really two pieces of it.

41
00:17:35,810 --> 00:18:01,250
One piece of it is this company understanding engine that helps you see how the product is changing. And then the other part of it is review. For the first part, the real competition is the workflows that these companies are engaging in on a daily basis. They have their status meetings, they've got their spreadsheet trackers, they have their issue management system. We have not found another technology product.

42
00:18:01,250 --> 00:18:18,050
That is solving this problem. It's made those conversations a lot easier with customers because to the extent that they've seen anything like Macroscope, it's way more metrics driven. It's like, oh yeah, I can see Dora metrics for how long PRs have been opened. But I think what a lot of those customers really want is, I want a qualitative change log.

43
00:18:18,050 --> 00:18:44,720
Around what's happening at the company. And so it makes the sort of positioning conversation a lot easier. For the other aspect of our product, it is a much more competitive space. Like everyone and their mother is building an AI code review tool. We were not the first, we're not going to be the last. And so really for our positioning, A, we had to know when we're talking to a customer, which do they care more about? Are they the CEO? If they're the CEO, they probably are more interested in understanding what their team is doing, how the product is changing, how the priorities are progressing.

44
00:18:44,720 --> 00:19:02,940
If it's the CTO, they maybe care about both. Maybe they're particularly trying to invest in, you know, AI tooling to make the team more productive. And so that's one part of the, I think, special sauce is just knowing upfront and asking them, like, what are the problems you're having and, like, where do you want to focus? Because our product can kind of help with both of these areas.

45
00:19:02,940 --> 00:19:31,950
But for CodeReview in particular, we had to spend way more energy explaining how we're different, like Will was talking about. For us, we have a technical bet that we've made with our product that we've essentially leveraged the AST for the engineers in this room. We leveraged the AST of all the programming languages that we support to create a graph of the customer's code base. We're really doing a lot of special sauce that has nothing to do with LLMs to set the LLMs up to be successful when we're doing inference.

46
00:19:31,950 --> 00:19:55,040
This is the thing that differentiates us from a lot of the other code review tools out there that have a more shallow understanding of the code base. When we talk to a customer about why our code review is different and why they should try it, we emphasize this technical approach that we've taken. That usually peaks their eyebrows because they're like, oh, cool, I've looked at a lot of code review tools and I haven't heard this approach.

47
00:19:55,040 --> 00:20:22,480
I'm still skeptical because I've seen a lot of these tools and they suck for one reason or another, but I'm interested in trying your tool because you've told me a story that is different than the story I've heard about the other tools. And so that I think was a core part of why we were able to get consideration in the early days from a lot of those customers. And then later on, it's like doing evals and benchmarks helps a lot because you can just show the proof in the pudding. And that's just yet another sort of data point that helps in the call.

48
00:20:22,510 --> 00:20:52,270
That makes sense. And you guys were, you know, you're starting with this position, you take hundreds of customer calls and refine and refine it. How do you then kind of decide like who you kind of care about in this space? Because like you have presumably hundreds of calls now under your bell. Are you deciding that like every one of them is ICP? Are you like kind of narrowing down to one for a particular reason? What did that process look like? You know, for us, we had to make a decision.

49
00:20:52,430 --> 00:21:21,440
There was an important point in our journey where we needed to decide when we were going to prioritize building features that would support larger companies. What I mean by that is our first 20 customers were, call it, under 50 engineers. We felt like we got the product pretty dialed for that size of company. Then we started talking to customers that were larger, like 100-plus engineers, and in some cases, multi-hundred-person engineering teams. When we first had those calls,

50
00:21:21,440 --> 00:21:44,720
It was just very clear from understanding how they felt this pain that the product as we had built it at the time just wasn't ready. And we had to make a call basically, all right, do we want to spend the next quarter working on features so that we could actually feel proud of the product for that customer? And, you know, there was a period where we just didn't, we weren't ready yet. We actually said, hey, thank you. Like, let us get back to you when we're ready to.

51
00:21:44,720 --> 00:22:13,330
You know, solve these pain points for you. And we actually circled back to those customers like two or three months later because we felt like we had to get our ducks in a row with the current customers that we were serving. So that was an important decision point for us. And we still have that decision ahead of us. Like we are, you know, actively in conversations with a few companies that are, you know, multi-thousand person engineering teams. And there's just, there are things that are different about the size of these code bases, about the specific programming languages that they use, or the specific workflows that they have, or

52
00:22:13,330 --> 00:22:35,970
They're compliance and security needs that we have to make a real prioritization decision around, hey, we're not going to burn a bunch of time on our roadmap or waste the customer's time until we can go back to them and say, we are ready to serve you. I think for us, we have to decide what those milestones were, and that definitely, there is more art than science there. It's really just a vibe check of like.

53
00:22:35,970 --> 00:23:03,200
How badly do we want to serve that tier of customer and how close are we based on what the product is actually capable of today? Yeah, I mean, it's probably worth us talking about this because I think the segmentation has been so, so important. I think we decided really early on as a company that we are going to compete with Salesforce for like the next four years because we just have so much to build. We have a radically different product and it's honestly just going to waste the team's time thinking about

54
00:23:03,200 --> 00:23:32,740
Salesforce migrations and the long tail of integrations. So we've always been thinking about building sort of a small business and startup company. And this interesting thing happened when we started to open up our waitlist, we got a pretty broad type of small business and startup, right? Where the next thing we knew, we had insurance companies, doctor's offices, construction companies, startups, vertical SaaS startups.

55
00:23:32,740 --> 00:23:57,730
And we sort of let them all in. And I think through that learned that a lot of the requirements were similar and that made us feel good about the sort of go-to-market approach, but there are also a lot of requirements that were different. And I would say that the big differences were around like what needs to be integrated, how is it integrated? You know, the sort of like workplace policy around privacy.

56
00:23:57,730 --> 00:24:24,380
And then we started to sort of break this up into clumps. One, there's a lot more similarity than difference among startups. And it was a great place to start. It's the people we knew. It's the people we are. And then two, we also had this other consideration that it's very hard to go viral. It's hard to build a big brand.

57
00:24:24,380 --> 00:24:43,710
When you start in small business alone, right? Because in this world where we like build for commercial real estate, which is actually like a growing segment of Lightfield, it's very hard to become like the de facto tool in commercial real estate and then jump to construction and then jump to, you know, compliance and then jump to...

58
00:24:43,710 --> 00:25:12,580
Startups because those industries aren't as networked as tech startups. So we sort of made this decision of, wait a minute, it seems like step one has to be startups because that's the only way to build a big brand. It's the only way to sort of like focus on fewer requirements, better, and then give us option value to get to the other parts of SMB later. So it was a little bit of, it was like a mix of reasons. Yeah, that's interesting. I mean, I think this network density thing is kind of an interesting

59
00:25:12,580 --> 00:25:40,340
I think to click on with a go-to-market that you want to be efficient. I mean, Will, you were saying earlier that, you know, you go to these events, right, where, you know, people that are looking for this sort of thing, or like at least larger financial institutions kind of gather in like a tight cluster, right, like one big room. Probably pretty important for that to be efficient. I'm curious, like, how that, I mean, I don't know how else you could sort of grow really quickly as a startup seeking that sort of audience. Curious if you can chime in on that.

60
00:25:40,340 --> 00:26:10,210
Yeah, and I'll tie this into the last conversation we just had, and I'll tell it, like, maybe in a story. We did YC in summer of 2023, and we had another company that was trying to do pretty much the same thing as us in a different space, and we took slightly different approaches. We both wanted to be an enterprise company, to Keith's point, like, where do you want to end up? We both wanted to be enterprise. They said, we're going to hold off until we can get our first 500K contract, essentially, and they're going to keep trying to get to that first 500K. We took a different approach. We're like, we'll use who wants to use us, right? Water through the pipes was the thought, and this was like,

61
00:26:10,210 --> 00:26:37,790
If you get more product usage, you can build a better and better product. So our first customer ever was like $5,000, and then it was $10,000, and that was $25,000, then it was $25,000 again, actually. Then it was $50,000, and then it went, so it started to go up and up. And we were at kind of like maybe $500,000 in revenue before that team had closed their first customer. And so I think there's a lot of value to getting, or at least in our world of B2B, getting water through the pipes, improving the product. And maybe it's, I don't know if this is financial services specifically, but it's very reputationally heavy.

62
00:26:37,790 --> 00:27:02,180
Every time you go into a bank, they're like, which other bank of our size is we using you? And the short answer for a while is none. And so you have to work your way up. I still remember, you know, our first logo that anyone knew was like Betterment. And like Betterment's an awesome company. We love them. They're a private company. That helped us close Robinhood, which is our first public company. And then Robinhood helped us close Mercury, Ramp, Gusto, Rippling, all these companies, which then helped us close multiple public companies. So it's like a ladder up.

63
00:27:02,180 --> 00:27:30,690
I don't think it would have been as successful if we were just like, we're going to only go work with JP Morgan, right? Even though directionally, like that's where we want to get to. So that was like one thought there. As it relates to building pipeline though, I think there's like two thoughts. It really depends on the go-to-market motion. I don't know. There's really like four go-to-market motions. There's like your SMB, your mid-market, your enterprise, and what you might call strategics. Each of those is a different go-to-market motion. We purely are in like the enterprise and strategic category today.

64
00:27:30,690 --> 00:27:55,040
