00:29:43,600 --> 00:30:11,810
Engineering variants, right? Like for us as programming languages, like our stack requires building discipline on a language by language basis. Like we started by serving Go and TypeScript repos because our stack is Go and TypeScript. And that allowed us to go, you know, we were shameless about leveraging our investors and their portfolio companies. We went and found all the customers in our, across our investor portfolio companies that, you know, leveraged Go and TypeScript for their repos.

70
00:30:11,810 --> 00:30:41,280
And then we would go unlock Python, and then we would go unlock Swift, and then we would unlock Java, and then Kotlin. And then, you know, so we sort of used that approach because it allowed us incredible with the engineering teams or the CTOs to say, hey, we just unlocked Python support. Here are all the customers we're serving with our product, which, you know, we had to qualify, right? Like it had to be appealing to them. But by going to them and saying, hey, we just spent a bunch of time making this work awesomely for Python codebases. We're ready to serve you. That sort of unlocked a channel for us that

71
00:30:41,280 --> 00:31:00,420
Also incidentally built credibility that, oh, wow, they're doing something special for Python-based codebases. That approach was really effective for us, but it was still your typical enterprise motion. For the larger companies, these are longer sales cycles. Still in our case,

