00:31:00,420 --> 00:31:23,940
No more than two months, it was still pretty fast given these are large companies. But now that we're launched publicly, we have this entire new section of the market that I think can come to the product, right? Like folks in this audience, you know, to the extent that you care about understanding what your team is working on and how the product is changing, you can just sign up on the website. And so there's more we need to do as a part of our go-to-market motion to sort of build interest and visibility and awareness.

73
00:31:23,940 --> 00:31:52,610
And so, yeah, we're still early in that journey, but it's an exciting new sort of fragment of the market for us. Makes sense. I think maybe one thing that both of you guys glossed over but is super important is you ultimately have to have a product that people love for any of this stuff to matter. And I found for us, it wasn't really until we had a product that people love that they were ready to talk about that any of this stuff started to like compound. Say that we...

74
00:31:52,610 --> 00:32:21,570
As of like a few months ago, we started to get this almost like, um, like virality coefficient, right? You make one customer happy, and they tell three other, uh, they tell three other, uh, customers about it, and then we get referrals. And that's sort of the, like, flywheel I think you need to build before all the, like, go-to-market tooling kicks in. Um, so I think that that's been, like, critical to our motion. And then maybe the other thing that's worth saying is that, um, you know, you've heard me use this bump.

75
00:32:21,570 --> 00:32:49,940
I think CEO of Bumble once said that you have to see the Bumble app seven times before you decide to download it. And so much of her early go-to-market was making sure that college students saw it seven times before caffeine season. And I think about that with us. We have a highly concentrated go-to-market. We're right now focused on

76
00:32:49,940 --> 00:33:02,910
Founders in Silicon Valley building great companies. Our caveman version of it is product works, need to make money, needs to be your mindset as a founder.

77
00:33:02,910 --> 00:33:29,420
Events are really great for that. This is the first of many that we're going to be running around founder-led sales. We're co-hosting hackathons. We're hosting a Gouda Market Bootcamp in a couple of months for a bunch of early-stage founders. And we found that if we can just be top of mind for you and we have customers that love our product, the rest will connect.

78
00:33:29,940 --> 00:33:59,520
I think it's interesting. I think there were several distinct moments, I can remember, at least five or six, where it felt like, oh, now closed beta is really starting. We started a closed beta, and then we got a few people interested enough through social posts, et cetera, to try the CRM. And then they'd be like, there's all these circumstances. There's just a few of them. They're busy. They might be trying it a little bit and not sure whether to actually use a CRM or not. And then over time, as we got a little bit closer to that,

79
00:33:59,520 --> 00:34:26,510
Product that I think served the sort of minimum requirement, then like the feedback started to kind of quickly become unmanageable. And then, you know, each of those moments kind of felt like its own kind of threshold that broke. Yeah, and I'm curious if you guys have had like sort of similar experiences where like the threshold sort of broke and you're like, oh shit, I could spend every waking moment of my day responding to these things. And like, you know, I need to like figure, I need some help.

80
00:34:27,790 --> 00:34:56,830
