81
00:34:56,830 --> 00:35:22,770
And the iterating on the product itself will not get you too, too far. Because again, it's never been as easy to make a product that looks great, at least in theory. And so I go to like, what am I seeing as paradigms that the founders I think are amazing and crushing it? It's like they value, they care, they work really intensely on go-to-market. They don't think of it as like something you hire salespeople for. It's something that you drive end-to-end. I'm saying this like, because there's founders in the room like.

82
00:35:22,770 --> 00:35:52,080
I don't want you to think like if you built this great product, it will do anything, like anything will come. You don't deserve anything for that. That's not, there's a hard part to it. But ultimately it's like building the business, willing it into existence is sales, especially in B2B. If you're doing something else, like willing it into existence, being embarrassed, like jumping on the plane to close that first 10K contract, that's the name of the game. It's less so. So that's where I might start there. When we started to see, like things started to work when we started to hear our names in, you know, hey, someone was talking about you here.

83
00:35:52,080 --> 00:36:22,020
So just successful outcomes from that customer doing it. But maybe I'll go back to like that view is you just need to help them with any problem worth solving. So I go back to like the product matters, but the problem you're solving is probably more important. In some ways, you might say this is like the constant thing of the Sequoia view of the world is like the market determines everything. That whatever the market you're tackling, it'll pull a great company out of you. It'll pull a great product out of you. I'm a strong subscriber of that camp. And that if you're solving a problem that matters enough and there's big enough budgets for it,

84
00:36:22,020 --> 00:36:51,790
It will carry you for a long period of time. And when you get to a competitive dynamic, then you just got to be super aggressive and push against it. I don't think AI is going to be top of mind for everyone for five more years. I think you have a year and a half to crush it, land it, be the biggest player in your category. And then from there, we might have the luxury of thinking about how do we make great moats or something like that. Maybe that's my school of thought in the world, especially because we're in a super competitive, dynamic environment. I don't know. Rambly answer, but that's how I was thinking about that question.

85
00:36:51,790 --> 00:37:17,360
I'm trying to think of how to answer this because there's two component parts of the question. When did we know things were working? And also, how did that influence our prioritization? But there was a lot of experimentation that we did around how to activate certain features in our product, both to

86
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:46,130
Maximally solve the customer problem, but then the way we built certain features really ended up inflecting how much our customers were liking the product and their likelihood of telling other customers. There's a few specific things that are very particular to our product that I'll share as stories. One of the first features we built is that homepage that I demoed. It shows you the pie chart of what your team is working on, and you can see how the projects have changed. When we first built that feature,

87
00:37:46,130 --> 00:38:13,500
You know, it just wasn't, it hadn't quite clicked for our customers, or like the usage of it didn't quite meet our expectations, let's say. And we sort of like beat our heads against the wall for a few weeks, and we ended up doing a very simple thing, which was building a feature that allowed the customer to sign up any number of emails to have that report at the end of the week automatically send to n number of email addresses. And that like, it was like the simplest thing, like that feature took like 30 minutes.

88
00:38:13,500 --> 00:38:42,350
But it completely unlocked for our existing customers. They're like, oh shit, I can send this to my CEO. I can send this to my CFO. I can send this to a bunch of other stakeholders that normally have no idea what's happening in product and engineering land. And then that just got the entire company, like at least the company's leadership team, bought in on like, let me go dive into this tool and see what's happening. And so it was just like a, if we hadn't have been kind of experimenting with other ways to activate that feature, it wouldn't have unlocked that visibility.

89
00:38:42,350 --> 00:39:07,490
Another very simple example, you know, I mentioned we have a code review tool, which typically like any other code review tool, we identify bugs in your PRs, we leave a comment in GitHub, you know, saying, hey, there's a bug here, here's how to fix it. The feature that we launched was like a simple add-on, but that really like set things on fire was we added a feature that let you have a long-running dialogue within the PR.

90
00:39:07,490 --> 00:39:34,500
Engineers sometimes want to ask clarifying questions like, are you sure this is a bug based on the behavior? Or maybe I want to fix this in a different way. And so we now have a fully interactive AI assistant that you can talk to. You can have it fix the bug. You can ask it clarifying questions and all that. And our team, in the early days, we were seeing every one of these interactions that customers were having. And as soon as we launched that feature, engineers at our customer companies were just having full-on conversations with the bot, basically.

91
00:39:34,500 --> 00:40:03,700
And it was so interesting because these conversations would sometimes have lots of personality in them. People would argue with the bot, people would compliment the bot, people would like really test the limits of it. And it sort of like went viral within the company. And I think it really accidentally, this was not our intention, but it accidentally really improved satisfaction of the product. And it sort of built credibility and trust that this bot is actually more sophisticated than you otherwise would have thought.

92
00:40:03,700 --> 00:40:29,150
We never would have changed the relationship that our users had with the product if we wouldn't have dabbled around the edges. Those two features are still the features that have our customers recommending to their friends at other companies. In some ways, I totally agree. It's so much of the success of any of these products is about to go to market, but there's also some

93
00:40:29,150 --> 00:40:56,720
Maybe it's the consumer founder in me that you do have to dabble around the edges to find the features that end up kind of going viral, even if viral means infecting the company internally with visibility around what the value proposition is. And that ended up being really important for us. That's funny. Well, it's a good provocation. I feel like there are definitely some spaces where there's a clear problem to solve. It's easy enough to solve it well, and it's just a land grab.

94
00:40:56,720 --> 00:41:26,190
Right? And you just have to go for it. And I totally agree with you, by the way. Now we have so much startup CRM data. And honestly, I could say, even with our, like, 10 of hundreds of customers, that the founders that do sales themselves tend to be the ones that build great companies. The founders that, like, do marketing themselves first before hiring people tend to be the ones that build great companies. And actually the ones that try to hire those people too early don't get very far.

95
00:41:26,190 --> 00:41:56,700
So I would totally agree with that. One, no one can sell the product like you. I think it's enthusiasm. It's how you sign and saying that you're going to fix something when shit goes wrong is, I think, required to move forward. And also, I think it gives you enough insight into how to run those departments well when you hire people.

96
00:41:56,700 --> 00:42:22,180
I completely agree with that, and on the land grab point, no question. I do think there are some spaces, though, where sooner or later you just need to have the best product, and I think a lot of the PLG are like that too, where there's like 10 for us, and we found just like...

97
00:42:22,180 --> 00:42:53,040
Having the one that feels nicest and is fastest actually goes a long way. And I think we talk about craft here a lot in terms of performance. It turns out fastest product does a whole lot of performance. And the other thing that I would say is that we sort of discovered this while building the company, but we found that there's gain in productivity for an account executive in our space.

98
00:42:53,040 --> 00:43:15,500
And that was an interesting realization where like, wait a minute, I don't think an LLM can make an AE-10X more productive. So as a result, it's going to be really hard to replace tools with that value prop. So we had this realization by being in hundreds of companies of, wait a minute, the thing that's really happening is we're like,

99
00:43:15,500 --> 00:43:42,080
We're making the engineers more productive because now they know what to build and they know how to write a PRD because they're connected to the customers and it's making the founder more productive because they can sharpen their ICP, which is a thing you never stop doing. I feel like even when you have a giant company... So I think that was the sort of discovery, for me at least, that what we have is interesting. I do think...

100
00:43:42,080 --> 00:44:10,720
I haven't been in YC, and I don't exactly know what the conversations there are like, but I feel like companies are starting to look pretty different now in terms of the people that are doing the selling are maybe traditionally engineers a lot of the time. And actually, there's a really high rate of pass-through of information that comes from customer conversations and hits the rest of the team, whatever function anyone plays. It's kind of interesting because I think on the flip side, I agree with...

101
00:44:10,720 --> 00:44:39,170
Part of your provocation, which is I think one of the best features that we have right now, or one of the things that I'm trying to work on as being a human feature, is responding to the Slack channels as soon as possible with the utmost attitude of service in these Slack channels. And I think it really does make a difference, especially when we have a lot of product holes to apologize for still. And then I think you have to think about the entropy that naturally occurs when you bring on additional people.

102
00:44:39,170 --> 00:45:06,400
Right? That also talk to those customers. And there's this interesting balance of like, you kind of want everyone to hear it from the horse's mouth as much as possible. But then I don't think you want someone to become the Oracle of the customer that like kind of passed through a lossy translation of the needs that is somehow less insightful than your original version. So I'm curious how you guys are thinking about that now, or if that's a question on your mind. Well, I mean, we do lots of little things that I think help.

103
00:45:06,400 --> 00:45:30,300
One, every customer conversation is recorded, transcribed, and published into Slack for every single team member, not just our engineering team, to see. I think it's a tiny thing, it's a feasible thing, but it's a really important thing. I know everyone on our team looks at that Slack channel when a new customer call ends and just reads through it. I know, because I get questions afterwards being like, why did they say this? And I think that's really, really important.

104
00:45:30,300 --> 00:45:54,860
Another little thing that we started very early on was we do rotations where I will just randomly pick an engineer from the team to join me on a customer call. Sometimes I'm thinking based on who can add value to this conversation or maybe they know someone who works at the company. Maybe they're just a huge fan of the product. I think that's a helpful way of building empathy amongst our engineering team of like,

105
00:45:54,860 --> 00:46:21,060
What are the customers actually saying? How does it sound when it comes out of their mouth? How much do they care about X, Y, or Z feature? And I think those things have been really helpful. And then the final thing I would add is just we truly do have an unfair advantage. And I think you guys are somewhat similar in this boat that we are customers of the product. We have so much intuition for the problems that our customers are facing because we face them ourselves.

106
00:46:21,060 --> 00:46:50,850
That there's like a separate prioritization problem of like, do we want to prioritize the problem as we feel it as a 17-person team? Or do we want to prioritize solving it for the 200-person engineering team? Like that's definitely gnarly. I have a lot of empathy for, I mean, you guys probably have less of that dynamic. You have a lot of understanding of the space, obviously, but I'm curious how much of that you feel as an internal engineering team. Are you sort of having to proxy for a lack of being able to feel the pain yourself?

107
00:46:50,850 --> 00:47:18,780
I don't know how many terrorists you have trying to use your internal tooling. You never know, really. So at first, it was pretty easy for the first 10 people. We had engineers very much involved with every one of the pre-sales and kind of also post-sales and implementation. So they were around and knew that pretty well. We have a proof of concept, proof of emotion. So before we start working with the customer, we start to get deeply embedded into their organization and hopefully help them solve a problem or two. That worked really well for 10 or so people. We're now about 35.

108
00:47:18,780 --> 00:47:45,040
And it's a little harder when you have to disseminate across those organizations. So the way we've structured it is just to be more intentional with our forward deployed engineering motion, of which it's our largest part of our engineering team. So simple examples of this is like, just like actually this morning, we agreed we're going to be in Europe in two weeks with engineers on site to help one of our largest customers go live with a new use case. And just like bringing them physically to the customer helps a lot.

109
00:47:45,040 --> 00:48:14,450
We do involve them a lot in the calls, so like the pre-sales and the post-sales. I think that becomes very, very important. We also spend a lot of time building up our deployment strategist team, which is broadly an incredible product meets customer success organization who are thinking about how do you solve problems by building product. So kind of like a forward deployed product manager is how we think about it. And so we're trying to put as many touchpoints as we can in the customer journey of meeting other members of the team. We also find it allows us to multi-thread. So again, when we go on site with this customer,

110
00:48:14,450 --> 00:48:38,480
Me and the sales guy are going to go meet everyone, shake hands, and kiss babies throughout the organization. The engineers can get to know the engineering counterparts. The deployment strategists can get to know the product managers. It allows us to cover more surface area in the accounts that we work with while also giving them the specialized knowledge that they need to succeed. And then as we think about scaling the team, we're always trying to think about how do we enable new account executives and go-to-market staff with knowledge of the product as well as the market.

111
00:48:38,480 --> 00:49:07,070
Something we're still working on, but we're trying to do as many training sessions as we can, getting them out to those events, hearing what their customers are saying and what their prospects are saying. So that's always a constant struggle for us is how do you enable people with the market intelligence and the product intelligence that they need to be successful? And on the engineering side, how do you equip them with new business context? We try to do that by bringing them on site. I have another very specific hack that is one of my favorite things that we do. I don't know how broadly applicable it is for the audience, but...

112
00:49:07,070 --> 00:49:35,940
Early on, we decided that we wanted to have shared Slack channels with every single customer. This made a ton of sense while we were in private beta, but this ended up being so effective that we not only do this for all of our enterprise customers, but for any self-serve customer. Like if anyone in this audience signs up for Macroscope right now, you'll see in our onboarding flow that we invite you to initiate a shared Slack channel that all the founders and all of our engineering leads join automatically. And this has become our de facto customer success.

113
00:49:35,940 --> 00:49:59,580
We support email and other mechanisms, but we prefer to have our engineers and your engineers and the founders and our founders in the same channel. And this is tremendous for a bunch of reasons. One, it shows the customer that you are serious about supporting them. I am often the very first person responding in any of these channels when our customers have a problem. And two, it allows our engineers to get

114
00:49:59,580 --> 00:50:28,460
The raw exposure to what are the CTOs and what are the IC engineers from our customers saying to us when they're sharing bugs, you're hearing it directly from the horse's mouth. I hope that there is not a point at which this no longer works. Thankfully, there are lots of great YC companies like Pylon trying to productize solutions to this problem, but I think for anyone in the audience that's in a similar B2B space, it's just such a simple thing that you can do that I think builds trust with your customers.

115
00:50:28,460 --> 00:50:57,980
And it's just more fun. I'd rather hear directly from our customers in a Slack channel. You sort of feel like you're on the same team. Well, one thing I was going to ask about is just, you said earlier today, Will, you're now looking for a VP of sales. If anyone knows a great VP of sales, talk to this guy. But I'm curious how you're thinking about bringing that person into the fold and letting them be an additional voice that...

116
00:50:57,980 --> 00:51:26,980
Reflects what the customer's needs are, and also has to internalize both the capabilities of your eng team and the needs of your market. It's funny, the version of what you just asked is not the angle I've always thought about it on. I've thought of way more mechanically in that each of our sales rep has a million or $1.5 million quota. I need to activate them as quickly as I possibly can, ramp them up as quickly as possible. Normally now it takes about six months to ramp them up to be fully productive.

117
00:51:26,980 --> 00:51:54,540
And if you know that, you can math your way into like, what are my goals for next year? How much capacity will I need? All right, I need someone to focus on hiring and enabling those people to be successful. And then there's a third part of this that I think about is like, how do you give them the structure they need such that they know when they're off the rails? So again, like one of our contracts will take eight to nine months to close. So you know the checkpoints and milestones you need to hit, you need someone to increase, like have that execution velocity there.

118
00:51:54,540 --> 00:52:24,180
And the fortunate thing as a founder, I'm not going to fully step away from go-to-market, have someone drive that component, but I get to jump a little bit more into a head of product style role. And that's how I anticipate working with that leader as they can communicate what we're hearing out for market while I still am a big part of most of those sales. But I anticipate that person to drive the rhythms, if you will. I think it's really important, though, to be involved for as long as humanly possible. And my thought here is we kind of think of go-to-market as one of two modes.

119
00:52:24,180 --> 00:52:53,540
Case study replication mode, like you've closed, I don't know, I'll just use an example, like Coinbase, and now you're going to go close Kraken. That's a case study replication. There's that mode of go-to-market where it's like repeatable and it's working well. I think that's something that VP sales can drive. Then there's the zero to one, like our first national bank. And I think it's much more important if the founders spend time on the zero to ones while setting up the case study replication. So it's funny, the way you framed it is not the way I thought about it. Like how do I bring online capacity?

120
00:52:53,540 --> 00:53:23,250
For an enterprise sales organization to be really effective while allowing me to spend more time, not on the individual account, but on the macro across the accounts. And that's how we're thinking about bringing on that leader and why we think they'd be helpful for us. We have a little bit of time now for Q&A. Anything else you want to jump into before we do that? So in the early stage of customer discovery, you kind of said that customer discovery is similar to doing sales.

121
00:53:23,250 --> 00:53:52,960
How do you initiate those calls? What do you say to get people to be on those calls, and how do you run them in the early days when it's kind of like an overlap between customer discovery and sales? Just jump in. Happy to start. I would cold DM people on LinkedIn. My exact message was something like, hey, I'm Will. I used to work on anti-money laundering systems at Facebook. We're now building something with AI in this space. I'd love to learn some of your pain points in this area. Send it out to hundreds and hundreds of people. Dozens responded.

122
00:53:52,960 --> 00:54:20,820
Of that dozen, 50% get on a call with you. You do a discovery call against it. At some point, you're like, oh, that pain point, that's actually what our product solves. Would you want to see a demo of that product? You bring them into a demo of that product. And again, we demoed it to like our first, before our first customer, we demoed it to maybe like 10 or so people. One person totally got it, like, hey, how much does it cost? Like, where can I put my credit card? And that was how we got our first sale. So big fan of just cold DMing on LinkedIn or emailing or calling, depending on your market.

123
00:54:20,820 --> 00:54:46,450
Asking them to do proper discovery with them, learn about their pain points. And then if you can help them, help them. If you can't help them, go back to them. Of that initial group of people we spoke to, many of them became customers later at another point in our journey because we ended up expanding features to solve them. So that was ours specifically for a B2B motion. A lot of what Will said resonated and was similar for us. The other thing I would add is just use every unfair advantage.

124
00:54:46,450 --> 00:55:11,630
You have available to you. In my case, I was shameless about saying, hi, I'm Kayvon. I started Periscope. I was the head of product at Twitter. I would love to show you the new product that I'm building and see if it resonates. You just got to spray and pray that to the people who you want to get on the phone with. Whatever the version of that is for you, I think the proof point of what you've worked on in the past can really resonate and be helpful.

125
00:55:11,630 --> 00:55:40,050
And then once you get more targeted with like the specific company, because at the beginning, you're just trying to learn. You're trying to understand what their problems are. And then over time, as you get more targeted with the specific companies that you want to get on the phone with, you can tailor that messaging a little bit more. Like for our version of that was, you know, we spent a lot of time, you know, building the best code review product for customers, you know, for companies that use Python repos. And we would just be very specific about like, we pre-qualified and know that you all are a big Python shop. And we're going to call that out so that this is like tailored.

126
00:55:40,050 --> 00:56:00,240
So those are some techniques that worked for us. Now, that end, use your investors. Like, we were shameless about asking our investors, hey, you know, such and such companies in your portfolio, we'd love to get on the phone with our CTO. Can you please introduce me? Totally agree with that. But one thing I would add is that I think at this stage of company building, you...

127
00:56:00,240 --> 00:56:28,830
You want to do stalker-level research on the people that you're trying to speak to, and that really worked for me. I found no AI outbounding tool has ever worked at this stage. When I reached out to people, I looked up the jobs they were posting, I looked up what they tweeted, what their LinkedIn post, what their VCs said about them, and then just try to form a hypothesis about the pain that they're feeling and show that you...

128
00:56:28,830 --> 00:56:57,820
That you're interested enough to help. And I think that's like the way to like overcome the, you might not have perfect experience relative to the company you're building. Like the founders, I know that do this well, they spend like two hours writing a LinkedIn message. And I would just like do things that don't scale at that stage. Next question. Hi, I'm Ashley. This question is specifically for Will, since I'm also...

129
00:56:57,820 --> 00:57:27,390
Looking at banks right now, like smaller banks, but also, like, we're basically doing customer discovery with a lot of different types of financial firms, and we're trying to figure out what type of financial firm would be the best, because I think one thing we realized was having a problem is one thing, but then finding the people who have the problem and are willing to solve it is another thing. So how do you kind of figure out, like, because we have noticed problems in different institutions, how do you figure out what type of

130
00:57:27,390 --> 00:57:53,810
Yeah, great question. I think it's all about the pain. How much are they feeling that pain? To your point, are they willing to solve it? The quick answer to that is how much are they willing to pay for it? I'm a big fan of using like, okay, great, you have this problem. How much would you pay for this thing? Or would you pay $50,000 or $100,000 to solve this problem? Chances are 90% of them will say no, and there's a 10% that eventually will say yes.

131
00:57:53,810 --> 00:58:23,330
If you don't ever hear yes after like 20 or 30 of those conversations, maybe it's not the right problem to solve. So I'm a huge fan of using like revenue as like a gating factor for how painful is this problem for you to solve, especially when you're talking to like a bank like that. And then urgency kind of comes out of that, right? Like, hey, if it's a hair on fire problem, they're probably willing to pay a little bit more if it was not a hugely important problem for them. I know that's overly simplistic, but revenue can actually tell you a lot about how meaningful of a problem that is for that bank.

132
00:58:23,330 --> 00:58:53,730
Thank you for the conversation. I have a question. What are some tips you have for early-stage founders for attending in-person events? Any hacks that worked for you? There are many founders today in the room. They're going to be going around for SF Tech Week. What did you do to maybe get those early customers and get the conversation started? I'm definitely not the best at this, but I think in general, building a business is just nonstop relationship building.

133
00:58:53,730 --> 00:59:20,930
And I think there's nothing more off-putting than someone trying to meet you and sell you a thing in like 30 seconds. So I found that people that are the best at this are just like really interested in people. So I think if you like try to form, if you have genuine curiosity and you show genuine interest in people, I think that these things will sort of come. And I would just be like comfortable with the fact that it'll take a while. Like it's unlikely you will meet.

134
00:59:20,930 --> 00:59:47,330
A person at an event who's ICP, who's ready to buy, who has your exact pain. But I think if you just show interest and demonstrate interesting point of views, that person might lead you to the right person. But that's just been my only take on it. You should probably have a bit of a social media presence. I say this as someone who sort of hates that part of my job, but I think you need to have enough

135
00:59:47,330 --> 01:00:15,780
Content, opinions, product out there so that people can sort of like grasp onto things when they speak to you. I don't know, you're the expert on this stuff. On social media? I'm not going to go down that rabbit hole right now. I think the only thing else I would add is just like show up and experiment and be ready. I mean, literally like today I showed up and Keith was like, do you want a demo? And I was like, sure, I guess. Like, you know, like I think you're right that there's sort of a

136
01:00:15,780 --> 01:00:46,910
It's a blurry line between just being authentic and getting to know people, but also being ready to show what you're building and why you're excited about it and how it works. And I think figuring out how that manifests depending on the venue, it just takes experimentation. Next question. Does this work? Okay. So I have a question. I'm in enterprise sales as well, and it's not a specific ICP. We have buying committees.

137
01:00:46,910 --> 01:01:17,140
Whole groups of people in a function that have to have consensus or some sort of majority in order to buy anything. For those of us who are reading the title of how to win your first 10 customers, in my mind, everybody in the buying committee is a customer. What's your advice or guidance around that? Because

138
01:01:17,620 --> 01:01:45,500
Initially starting the sales process and using the Lightfield product, I initially thought the customer was the company, but the customer's not a company. It's everybody that's in the buying committee. What advice do you have about buying committees and selling a product? Thank you. Yeah, happy to help. Fortunately, this is what you might call a solve problem. People have thought about this when they sell these big...

139
01:01:45,500 --> 01:02:15,220
The things I would research is things like MedPIC, qualification frameworks and structures for doing enterprise sales. A very simple thing is in that type of world, for a buying committee, you need a champion who feels the pain specifically and has influence enough on the buying committee that they can sway things. You also, as the founder, when I know all the stakeholders involved and your champions say, hey, who are the eight people that need to make this and who's on the buying committee? I try, beg, borrow, and steal to try and get in front of each member of that team.

140
01:02:15,220 --> 01:02:44,670
Understand their unique needs. As quickly as like, hey, I'm talking with John in this department. He said, you guys are thinking about this purchase. Do you have 10 minutes? I just want to make sure I'm getting your perspective around the table. People love that kind of stuff. You need influence everyone on that table, but you need someone to push you through the buying committee. Again, if I go back to, if someone says, oh, it's a buying committee, it's not my decision, they're probably not your champion or the pain point's not painful enough. Like we sell the banks that normally take years and we have closed things in five to six months.

141
01:02:44,670 --> 01:03:14,800
If you find a strong enough pain point and a strong enough champion. Yeah. In the early days, how did you guys manage the building of features and offerings for maybe a design partner versus someone that you're really wanting to close and they say, oh, this would be great, but we would love to see this and that informing your product? I mean, I think this is the hardest part in our space. I'm not sure how to answer it other than saying that it's just...

142
01:03:14,830 --> 01:03:43,090
It's a lot of vibes and a lot of like, which customer do you want to prioritize first? How strategic is it to unlock a new category of customer by building X, Y, and Z features? And how much of the pain did that customer feel? Was this a burning hair on fire problem for that customer? Or were they like, yeah, I mean, this seems interesting. If you did X, Y, and Z. Sometimes when you hear the, if you did X, Y, and Z, it's just sort of an excuse.

143
01:03:43,090 --> 01:04:11,380
It's easier for them to say that than to say, this just isn't an important thing for me right now. You need to vibe check which of those it is. Sometimes, genuinely, it's like, I really want to use this tool, but because of X, Y, and Z reason, it's just not going to work for us unless you build these features. If it's a really large customer that we really want because they were passionate about what we were building and we thought they'd be a great design partner for us, we would drop what we're doing and go build those features.

144
01:04:11,380 --> 01:04:37,410
We sort of had to develop an intuition for other times when we heard that. We were like, okay, they're just not really bought in. Like, whatever we're building is not resonating with them. We're not going to go disrupt our roadmap to go build those features because it sounds like a recipe for a goose chase. You just have to feel out which it is and prioritize accordingly. That's a really good insight. I think it applies to sales, recruiting, fundraising. But I think that there's like...

145
01:04:37,410 --> 01:04:54,270
Often a customer or someone you're working with who has this mindset of, I really want to use this platform and I just need X to make it work. And I think you need to find those relationships. It's sort of your job as a founder to find those. And then you'll hear a lot of like, I don't, I can't.

146
01:04:54,270 --> 01:05:21,980
If you did X, maybe I'll use your product. Or if you got to X milestone, maybe I would want to fund you. Or if you guys were a little smaller, this would make more sense. And I think that's always just the San Francisco conflict-avoidant way of passing. And I think you just have to develop a barometer for that. The other sort of tactic we use to try and tease those things apart is for customers that

147
01:05:21,980 --> 01:05:51,820
This was relevant for where they're like, well, we sort of need X, Y, and Z. We would ask them to sign up and we would just decide upfront, like, hey, instead of a one-month trial, we're going to give you a three-month trial. We think it's going to take us three months to build all these things that we talked about. And we are willing to prioritize that if you're willing to sign up today. And that's like a very helpful way to tease out, like, how invested are they? Because if they are invested, they'll be like, cool, I'm going to take your word for it that in three months, this will be ready. I'm willing to go through the process of an

148
01:05:51,820 --> 01:06:21,520
Vesting in you and doing the onboarding and all that stuff. And then, you know, the value exchange is that we're not going to charge you until we're proud of the solution we've built for you. And if they're not willing to do that, that's a signal, right? That tells you, well, they're kind of like not sold enough to even do a free design partnership for some period of time. I think these dynamics change once the product is more mature. Like we wouldn't do the same sort of thing now that we've launched publicly. But when we were six months in and we're just trying to find design partners, that was extremely useful.

149
01:06:22,290 --> 01:06:51,980
Awesome. Last question. Hi. All right. Very cool. Yeah, I guess my question is back to how you mentioned founder sales, a lot of it is discovery, especially winning your first 10 customers. That is a lot of figuring out who your ICP, what value prop. I just want to hear more, I guess, in terms of your experiences, how long did that take you? And also, how much did...

150
01:06:51,980 --> 01:07:18,240
Your product, your value proposition, your ICP changed, and how did you navigate through that? How do you know that it was the value prop that isn't good enough, or maybe the ICP that isn't correct, or the product? Having to start, I think we did that discovery of DMing people, asking them questions when we were at zero revenue for three or four months of that, just learning the product that we wanted to build.

151
01:07:18,240 --> 01:07:44,460
When we had the product that we wanted to build, we essentially did a public launch that, hey, this is the product we're building, this is the main point we solve. We had people who came inbound, and from that moment to like our first customer was about a week. And that's because we did a lot of discovery ahead of time. We front-loaded a lot of that conversations. In terms of how it shifted, the products were like the problem, because again, we're solving like this boring B2B problem that we love. The problems stay the same. It's just the scale and complexity of it increased.

152
01:07:44,460 --> 01:08:08,930
Over time, you need more bells and whistles to serve a public company versus a, you know, 20-person fintech in our world. But the product stayed remarkably similar over time. For us, you know, we, again, we had sort of two versions of our product, right? We have code review and we have this understanding engine piece. And for the latter, similar to what Will was saying, like the complexity and the bells and whistles we needed.

153
01:08:08,930 --> 01:08:35,810
To serve different tranches of customers changed quite a bit, but the actual value proposition, the story we told, was like fundamentally pretty similar. And it all sort of was grounded in the early customer discovery we did. We sort of understood the pain points that CEOs and heads of product and heads of engineering had when they were trying to understand how things were changing. What really changed about our positioning was when we started building features that served engineers, like IC engineers, which are code of the future.

154
01:08:35,810 --> 01:09:02,689
It does. We're building code review not for the CEO. We're building code review to solve problems, save time for IC engineers. We really had to adapt our story. When we're talking to a CTO, how do we tell the story? How do we make sure we show them the features we're building for them and also how we're solving problems for their IC engineer? That part of our sales pitch is admittedly complicated because we're building some things for the actual customer who's paying us.

155
01:09:02,689 --> 01:09:29,939
But we're also building some features for their constituents. And it's sort of like we have to tease apart that story. And it took us a bit of iteration to nail that messaging. It was probably like a couple of months of taking some swings and iterating and just kind of feeling like we muddled through the story. But again, you just have to experiment. Like I would change my pitch and the ordering of my demo and what I showed and what I showed with every conversation.

156
01:09:29,939 --> 01:10:00,290
It was pretty clear afterwards based on my own vibe check and also how badly did they want to move forward. You can just tell these things. As long as you're pushing yourself to iterate, I think you'll find your own path towards a pitch that resonates and feels localized. I'll give the really short answer and then we can just all informally chat after. It took us a while. It took us probably over a year.

157
01:10:00,290 --> 01:10:28,770
And I would say that it's one of those problems that you actually need to solve for all variables at once. You can't quite isolate because like a great company means that you're solving a problem for someone, they're happy with your solution, and you can efficiently get more customers like that that will pay you enough to build the entire product and company, right? So I think the worst way to look at this is like let me hold

158
01:10:28,770 --> 01:10:56,160
Four variables constant, and then try to find the go-to-market engine, or let me hold the customer constant, and then try to find the other piece. You sort of have to solve for it all at once. And it can take a week, it can take a year, it could take five years. I think there's companies like Figma and Roblox that it took half a decade for it to click, but when you know, you know. And what I mean by that is...

159
01:10:56,160 --> 01:11:14,960
Things start to feel easy. And I'll give you some examples of what starts to feel easy. For us, like a leading indicator was the number of calls we have that move to trial. Like when it was hard, it was like one in ten, you know, and at some point it was like...

160
01:11:14,960 --> 01:11:43,650
9 out of 10. And we're like, oh, interesting. Maybe we can go and get more of these people. And then another sign that it was easy was going from trial to ready to pay. And when it was hard, it was like 4 out of 10. And then at some point, everyone that activated was ready to pay. And then the other piece was, I think the worst part of being a founder is if you have a product where people have apathy.

161
01:11:43,650 --> 01:12:11,040
They don't hate it, they don't love it, it's just sort of there. And I think you want to get to a state where your product is so important to people that they're yelling at you about all of the things that it needs to do in addition to its core. And I think we woke up one day and we were just flooded with pylon and slap tickets, and there was this step change for the company, but I would be discerning about it.

162
01:12:11,040 --> 01:12:40,460
It might take a little longer than you want, but getting to that, the right hill is really important. Maybe going back to Kayvon, your example of finding someone that is really excited to use your thing and maybe doesn't have everything that they need yet and trying to discern the authenticity of that desire and trying to replicate or study that interaction. What are they into about what I'm selling?

163
01:12:40,460 --> 01:13:10,460
Is that true about everyone else in the organization, other folks, other types of companies in the market? And I think it is constantly rotating this pizza dough almost where it's like, you're shaping this thing, it's really unstructured, but eventually you want it to kind of be a circle. One quick little hack that that reminded me of, going back to your question. One thing that we did that was really effective for our customers that were really getting value out of the product and using it, we would just ask them. Because early on, we kind of didn't know exactly how to describe this.

164
01:13:10,460 --> 01:13:39,100
It was this amorphous blob that we were still building. So we just ask our customers, like, now that you've used the product for two months, like, what is this team? Like, how would you describe the product back to me? Like, when you go tell your team about this new tool you're about to roll out, like, what is your one-liner? And that was really insightful because oftentimes the way they explained the product was not the way we had sort of trained ourselves to pitch it. And I think getting a reality check on that as time goes on is actually really useful. Like, six months goes by, like, ask the same customers, like,

165
01:13:39,100 --> 01:13:49,680
What is the product to you? Awesome. Will, Kayvon, Keith, thank you so much for joining us today. And thank you all for coming to listen.

